    <h3>Where Lentor Gardens shines</h3>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Growth hotspot (5&#9733;).</strong> The site sits <em>inside</em> the official Lentor Growth Hotspot zone. That&rsquo;s a structural tailwind &mdash; URA-coordinated infrastructure, amenity densification and master-plan investment compound over a 10-year hold.</li>
      <li><strong>GLS pipeline (5&#9733;).</strong> Seven future GLS plots within a 2&nbsp;km radius. Each successful subsequent land bid resets the precinct&rsquo;s entry pricing upward &mdash; and Lentor Gardens, having entered cheapest, captures the widest margin from that uplift.</li>
      <li><strong>Project size (5&#9733;).</strong> ~500 units lands squarely in the sweet spot &mdash; large enough to spread maintenance fees and support deep facilities, small enough to preserve a community feel. Resale liquidity stays healthy.</li>
      <li><strong>Remaining tenure (5&#9733;).</strong> A ~98-year balance gives a clean 20-year-plus exit window with zero immediate lease-decay drag.</li>
      <li><strong>MRT connectivity (4&#9733;).</strong> A 7-minute walk to Lentor MRT (TE5) is solidly above the OCR average. Not a 3-minute MRT walk, but well within the rentability band.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Where it doesn&rsquo;t</h3>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>School effect (1&#9733;).</strong> No popular primary school sits within the 1&nbsp;km registration radius. The wider Ang Mo Kio belt (CHIJ St. Nicholas, Anderson Primary) is reachable, but the strict 1&nbsp;km premium &mdash; the one that anchors rental and resale demand independent of the property cycle &mdash; isn&rsquo;t at this address.</li>
      <li><strong>MOP / upgrader cluster (2&#9733;).</strong> Approximately 919 HDB / BTO units within 2&nbsp;km expected to reach MOP in the next 10 years &mdash; a steady demand pool, but below the 1,000+ threshold where the framework awards a higher score. There is upgrader interest; there isn&rsquo;t a tidal wave.</li>
      <li><strong>Rental yield (3&#9733;).</strong> Projected ~3.3% gross yield is bang-on the OCR average. Adequate cash-flow cover, but not the headline you&rsquo;ll see in a CCR project with a 1&nbsp;km elite school catchment.</li>
    </ul>

