    <h2>Who is Lentor Gardens Residences actually for?</h2>

    <p>Strip away the launch noise and the buyer profile is unusually clean:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Entry-price-led OCR investors</strong> &mdash; buying the lowest land cost in a precinct that&rsquo;s actively rebenchmarking upward is one of the cleanest setups OCR offers right now.</li>
      <li><strong>Long-horizon capital-growth buyers</strong> &mdash; positioning ahead of the next 5&ndash;10 years of Lentor master-plan execution rather than chasing the rebound this quarter.</li>
      <li><strong>Multi-generational families considering the strata terrace homes</strong> &mdash; three units, one shot, no comparable product in the area.</li>
      <li><strong>Owner-occupiers who care about layout</strong> &mdash; non-PPVC + dumbbell layout + true-sized rooms is a meaningful upgrade over the cookie-cutter PPVC norm.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>It&rsquo;s a weaker fit if your priority is a 1&nbsp;km elite primary school catchment, or if your underwriting depends on a wave of nearby HDB upgraders driving a 3&ndash;5 year resale flip. Neither lever is at maximum intensity at this address.</p>

    <p>As always, the responsible next step is to <em>see the data before you see the showflat</em>. Read the PrimeKey Report above, line it up against any other Lentor or OCR shortlist you&rsquo;re considering, and decide on facts &mdash; not on the brochure&rsquo;s rendering quality.</p>

